{"type":"message","id":"d8c93a5b","parentId":"7d030c28","timestamp":"2026-03-22T13:09:46.736Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is saying the VS Code extension market is too crowded. Component Crate is off the table. Let me check what other monetization paths exist in his project inventory. From the active-projects list:\n\n- EXP/CAAE — LLM inference optimization, strong B2B SaaS potential\n- temporal-attention — working, 10/10 hard tests\n- infant — published, MIT licensed\n- selfhelper-main — working autonomous agent\n- Breakaway (sandbox) — Phase 0 live\n\nHe needs revenue. The crowded field verdict on component-crate means we need to think about what else has monetization path.\n\nLooking at the Schemocker conversation - this IS a project of his (toxzak-svg/schemocker). \n\nSchemocker has real potential as a paid SaaS tool, and the MCP angle sets it apart from the crowded component space. Since he doesn't have GPU access for Ollama, I should ask what he actually wants to build right now—maybe revisit the Schemocker AI features using cloud-based AI instead, or check what's actually feasible given his current constraints.","thinkingSignature":"286269a08a3bfe2562d01eef6c762f6da8017f6cfe3057f90135cbdf7989b51b"},{"type":"text","text":"Fair. Crowded market, hard to break in.\n\nSo what's left that has a real monetization path? Schemocker is yours — it's a real product with a real differentiator (MCP-first, single binary). The AI features in the plan don't actually *need* local GPU — you can wire all of them to OpenAI or Anthropic API, which is cheap for the schema inference use case (tiny prompts, infrequent calls).\n\nThe play would be: **Schemocker Pro** — free tier uses OpenAI for AI features, paid tier unlocks higher rate limits + custom schema templates + team features. The MCP server is already the moat.\n\nAlternatives from the project list:\n- **EXP/CAAE** — B2B SaaS targeting startups/cos who want LLM inference optimization. Real product, real pain point.\n- **temporal-attention** — could be an API/service (focus decay memory for agents)\n- **selfhelper-main** — autonomous agent, harder monetization story\n\nWhat's catching your eye this morning?"}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":440,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":29109,"totalTokens":29592,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774184968458}}
{"type":"message","id":"3721eed6","parentId":"d8c93a5b","timestamp":"2026-03-22T13:10:38.154Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Sun 2026-03-22 09:10 EDT] Now I have the full picture — no existing users means no constraints at all. Here's the real talk:\n\n***\n\nSince there are no existing users, you have a rare opportunity: **don't add AI to Schemocker — rebuild the core identity around AI and let the current mock-server infrastructure be the engine underneath.** The positioning shifts from \"mock server that has an MCP bolt-on\" to \"describe your API in plain English, get a running mock instantly.\"\n\n## What the MCP Server Currently Is\n\nLooking at [`src/mcp-server/index.ts`](https://github.com/toxzak-svg/schemocker/blob/main/src/mcp-server/index.ts), it exposes exactly 4 tools: `list_routes`, `call_endpoint`, `reload_schema`, and `world_snapshot` . It's read/call oriented — an AI can *explore* your mock, but it can't *create or mutate* the schema through the MCP interface at all . That's the biggest gap.\n\n## What to Add to the MCP Server First\n\nAdd these 3 tools directly to `getAvailableTools()` in `src/mcp-server/index.ts` :\n\n- **`generate_schema`** — accepts a natural language description, calls an LLM, returns a valid JSON Schema, and hot-reloads it into the running server. This is the killer feature: `\"I need a social media post with likes, comments, and author\"` → live endpoint in seconds.\n- **`mutate_schema`** — takes the current schema + a NL instruction like `\"add a createdAt timestamp field\"` and returns a merged updated schema. Calls the same LLM adapter.\n- **`seed_world`** — tells the world-state engine to populate N realistic records using LLM-generated values for semantic fields (biography, description, title) rather than faker noise.\n\n## The Core Architecture Shift: Add `src/ai/`\n\nSince there are zero users to break, rip out any \"optional flag\" thinking. Make `src/ai/` a **first-class module** with:\n\n```\nsrc/ai/\n provider.ts ← abstract interface: .complete(prompt) → string\n openai.ts ← OpenAI adapter\n ollama.ts ← local Ollama adapter (point at your A5000s)\n vllm.ts ← your own vLLM server adapter\n schema-inferrer.ts ← NL → JSON Schema via prompt template\n field-enricher.ts ← semantic field name → realistic LLM value\n```\n\nThe `provider.ts` interface is just `complete(prompt: string): Promise<string>`. Every other module in `src/ai/` calls through that. This means you can demo it with OpenAI, run it privately on Ollama, or plug in your KViction-optimized vLLM endpoint — the same codebase.\n\n## What to Change in `src/generators/schema-routes.ts`\n\nThis is the faker engine . Right now it matches field formats (UUID, email, date) deterministically. Add a **semantic field detector** here:\n\n```typescript\n// if field name contains: description, bio, title, summary, comment, review, message\n// AND ai provider is configured\n// → call fieldEnricher.generate(fieldName, parentSchema)\n// ELSE → existing faker logic\n```\n\nThis is a zero-breaking-change enhancement that makes generated data dramatically more useful for demos and screenshots.\n\n## What to Remove / Simplify\n\nSince there are no users, you can be ruthless:\n\n- **Kill the `--scenario` flags** (`slow`, `error-heavy`, `sad-path`) as separate CLI concerns — fold them into the MCP `call_endpoint` tool as optional parameters. They add CLI surface complexity that clutters first impressions.\n- **Kill the 6 example schemas** as the primary pitch — replace with one command: `schemock init \"a blog with users, posts, and comments\"`. The LLM generates the schema, boots the server. That *is* the pitch.\n- The `world-state.ts` snapshot/mutation model is actually a strong foundation — keep it but expose it fully through MCP so an AI agent can do CRUD loops against the mock world during agentic testing workflows.\n\n## Repositioning the README\n\nThe current pitch is *\"frontend devs blocked waiting on backend\"* . That's a fine niche but small and commoditized. The stronger AI-era pitch is: **\"Describe your API. Your AI agent gets a live endpoint to test against. No schema writing, no backend, no waiting.\"** That's a workflow tool for AI-assisted development — a much faster growing category, and it uses the MCP server you already built as the actual differentiator."}],"timestamp":1774185038146}}
{"type":"message","id":"7e7e4680","parentId":"3721eed6","timestamp":"2026-03-22T13:11:31.853Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Zach is giving me the full updated picture - he wants me to update the PLAN.md with these changes. Let me rewrite it based on his revised strategy.\n\nKey changes from his message:\n1. No users = no constraints, rebuild core identity around AI\n2. The MCP server should be the primary interface, not the CLI\n3. Add 3 MCP tools: `generate_schema`, `mutate_schema`, `seed_world`\n4. `src/ai/` is a first-class module with provider abstraction\n5. `schema-routes.ts` gets semantic field detector\n6. Kill `--scenario` flags, fold into MCP `call_endpoint` params\n7. Kill the 6 example schemas, replace with `schemock init \"description\"`\n\n\n8. README repositioned around \"Describe your API, AI agent gets a live endpoint\"\n\nNow I need to update PLAN.md with all these revisions.","thinkingSignature":"bcfbf78a6593a8c12b352e1fc3ee55d57ebe51347dc749a5c9e99107b4ffbd80"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_fxpiyi1whyiy_1","name":"write","arguments":{"content":"# Schemocker — AI-Native Rewrite Plan\n\n> **Core Identity Shift:** Schemocker is no longer a mock server with an MCP bolt-on. It is an **AI-first API authoring tool** — describe your API in plain English, get a running mock endpoint instantly. The MCP server is the primary interface, not a feature.\n\n> **Zero users = zero constraints.** Rip, replace, and rebuild.\n\n---\n\n## Repositioning\n\n| Before | After |\n|---|---|\n| \"Frontend devs blocked waiting on backend\" | \"Describe your API. Your AI agent gets a live endpoint. No schema writing, no waiting.\" |\n| MCP server is a bolt-on feature | MCP server is the primary interface — AI agents drive everything |\n| `schemock start <schema>` + examples | `schemock init \"a blog with users, posts, and comments\"` → live server |\n| Scenario flags (`--scenario slow/error/sad-path`) | Fold into MCP `call_endpoint` as optional params |\n| 6 example schemas as the onboarding | One NL command, one server |\n\n---\n\n## MCP Server — `src/mcp-server/index.ts`\n\n**Current state:** 4 read/call tools — `list_routes`, `call_endpoint`, `reload_schema`, `world_snapshot`. AI can explore but not create or mutate.\n\n**Replace with — 7 tools:**\n\n### Keep (modified)\n- `list_routes` — unchanged\n- `call_endpoint` — add `scenario?: 'slow' | 'error' | 'sad-path'` as optional param (kills CLI flag surface)\n- `reload_schema` — unchanged\n- `world_snapshot` — unchanged\n\n### Add\n- **`generate_schema`** — natural language description → valid JSON Schema → hot-reload into running server. The killer feature. Example: `\"I need a social media post with likes, comments, and author\"` → live endpoint in seconds.\n- **`mutate_schema`** — current schema + NL instruction → merged updated schema. Example: `\"add a createdAt timestamp field\"` → schema updated and hot-reloaded.\n- **`seed_world`** — populate N realistic records using LLM-generated values for semantic fields (bio, description, title, review) rather than faker noise.\n\n---\n\n## New Module: `src/ai/` — First-Class, Not Optional\n\n```\nsrc/ai/\n├── provider.ts       # Abstract interface: complete(prompt: string): Promise<string>\n├── openai.ts         # OpenAI adapter\n├── ollama.ts         # Local Ollama adapter (Zach's A5000s when available)\n├── vllm.ts           # Self-hosted vLLM adapter (CAAE/EXP inference stack)\n├── schema-inferrer.ts    # NL → JSON Schema via prompt template\n└── field-enricher.ts    # Semantic field name → realistic LLM value\n```\n\n**`provider.ts` interface is one method:**\n```typescript\nexport interface AIProvider {\n  complete(prompt: string): Promise<string>;\n}\n```\n\nEverything in `src/ai/` calls through this. OpenAI for demos, Ollama for local, vLLM for private infrastructure — same interface.\n\n### Ollama path\nNo A5000 = Ollama on the laptop. Qwen2.5-3B is fast enough for schema inference and field enrichment. `ollama serve` locally, `http://localhost:11434`.\n\n### vLLM path (for when GPU situation resolves)\nPoints at the Paperspace endpoint. Same adapter interface, just different base URL + auth.\n\n---\n\n## `src/generators/schema-routes.ts` — Semantic Field Detector\n\nAfter existing faker logic runs, check each field name for semantic content:\n\n```typescript\n// if field name contains: description, bio, title, summary, comment,\n//                       review, message, body, content, bio, tagline, tagline\n// AND AI provider is configured\n// → call fieldEnricher.generate(fieldName, parentSchema)\n// ELSE → existing faker logic\n```\n\n**Zero breaking change** — only activates when AI provider is set. Makes generated data dramatically more useful for demos and screenshots.\n\n---\n\n## `src/generators/world-state.ts`\n\nStrong foundation — keep it. Expose fully through MCP so AI agents can do CRUD loops against the mock world during agentic testing workflows. The `seed_world` MCP tool calls into this.\n\n---\n\n## Simplifications (No Users = No Constraints)\n\n### Kill\n- ~~`--scenario slow/error-heavy/sad-path`~~ → fold into `call_endpoint(scenario?)` as optional param\n- ~~6 example schemas as primary onboarding~~ → replaced by `schemock init \"NL description\"`\n- ~~`--ai-enrich` flag~~ → AI features activate automatically when `schemock.json` has `ai:` block or env vars set\n\n### Keep\n- Single binary (zero deps)\n- Hot reload\n- CORS on by default\n- All existing test suite\n\n---\n\n## New CLI Entry Point\n\n```bash\nschemock init \"a blog with users, posts, and comments\"\n# → LLM generates schema\n# → Server boots with all routes live\n# → MCP server running\n\nschemock init --interactive\n# → Prompt loop for iterative schema building\n```\n\nImplementation: `src/cli/commands/init.ts` — calls `schema-inferrer.ts`, writes schema to disk, boots server.\n\n---\n\n## `schemock.json` — AI Config Block\n\n```json\n{\n  \"version\": \"1.0.0\",\n  \"ai\": {\n    \"provider\": \"openai\",\n    \"model\": \"gpt-4o-mini\",\n    \"apiKey\": \"env:SCHEMOCKER_API_KEY\"\n  },\n  \"defaults\": {\n    \"port\": 3000,\n    \"cors\": true\n  }\n}\n```\n\nDefaults to OpenAI `gpt-4o-mini` (cheapest, fast enough for schema work). User swaps to `ollama` or `vllm` when ready.\n\n---\n\n## README Repositioning\n\n**Current pitch:** \"Frontend devs blocked waiting on backend\"\n\n**New pitch:**\n> **\"Describe your API. Your AI agent gets a live endpoint to test against.\"**\n>\n> Drop a schema → get a mock. Or don't write one at all. Tell Schemock what you need in plain English and it generates the schema, boots the server, and exposes everything over MCP. Your AI agent (Claude, Cursor, any MCP client) can explore, create, and mutate the mock directly — no schema writing, no backend, no waiting.\n\n---\n\n## Priority Order\n\n| # | Task | Why |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1 | Write `src/ai/provider.ts` interface | Foundation for everything |\n| 2 | Write `src/ai/openai.ts` adapter | Fastest path to working |\n| 3 | Add 3 MCP tools to `src/mcp-server/index.ts` | Core of the new identity |\n| 4 | Wire `generate_schema` to schema-inferrer | The killer feature |\n| 5 | `schemock init \"NL description\"` CLI command | New primary onboarding |\n| 6 | Semantic field detector in `schema-routes.ts` | Quick win, high impact |\n| 7 | `seed_world` MCP tool → world-state | Makes demos look real |\n| 8 | `ollama.ts` adapter | Local-first when A5000 available |\n| 9 | README rewrite | New positioning |\n| 10 | `vllm.ts` adapter | CAAE/EXP showcase (deferred until GPU resolves) |\n\n---\n\n## Files to Create / Modify\n\n```\nsrc/ai/\n+ provider.ts          [NEW — interface]\n+ openai.ts            [NEW — adapter]\n+ ollama.ts            [NEW — adapter]\n+ vllm.ts              [NEW — adapter, deferred]\n+ schema-inferrer.ts   [NEW]\n\nsrc/mcp-server/\n~ index.ts             [MODIFY — add 3 tools]\n\nsrc/cli/commands/\n+ init.ts              [NEW — schemock init]\n\nsrc/generators/\n~ schema-routes.ts     [MODIFY — semantic field detector]\n\nschemock.json          [MODIFY — add ai: block]\n\nREADME.md              [REWRITE]\n```\n\n---\n\n## vLLM / A5000 Situation\n\nPaperspace Gradient notebooks aren't a viable self-hosted path right now (session management, cold starts). When a real GPU endpoint is available, `vllm.ts` adapter drops in with the same interface. The abstraction holds regardless.\n\nOllama on laptop = fully functional for development + demos.\n\n---\n\n*Plan version: 2.0 | AI-native rewrite 2026-03-22*\n","file_path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\schemocker-tmp\\PLAN.md"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":43,"output":2031,"cacheRead":29378,"cacheWrite":938,"totalTokens":32390,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774185038152}}
